","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Johnstone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Johnston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Johnston","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, deriving in most cases from the place so called in Annandale, in Dumfriesshire. This is derived from the genitive case of the personal name   John   + + Middle English <i>ton</i> ‘town, village, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). There are other places in Scotland so called, including the city of Perth, which used to be known as <i>Saint John's Toun</i>, and some of these may also be sources of the surname.","English: habitational name from Johnson Hall (Staffordshire), recorded as <i>Johanneston</i><i>c.</i> 1233 and <i>Joneston</i> in 1314. The placename means ‘John's settlement’, from the genitive case of the Middle English personal name <i>Johan</i>, <i>Jon</i> (see   John  ) + Middle English <i>ton</i> ‘town, village, settlement’.","History: As far as can be ascertained, most Scottish bearers of this surname are descendants of John, probably a Norman baron from England, who held lands at Johnstone in Annandale from the Bruce family in the late 12th century. His son Gilbert was the first to take the surname Johnstone and their descendants later held the earldom of Annandale."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert Of Johnstone was born in Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland as the son of Sir John Johnstone. He had at least 1 son. He died after 1309."},"et":{"–After 1309":"–pärast 1309","–1309":"–1309","1305–1370":"1305–1370","–1296":"–1296","1305":"1305","After 1309":"pärast 1309","1296":"1296","after 1296":"pärast 1296","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"–After 1309":"–1309 jälkeen","–1309":"–1309","1305–1370":"1305–1370","–1296":"–1296","1305":"1305","After 1309":"1309 jälkeen","1296":"1296","after 1296":"1296 jälkeen","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"–After 1309":"–après 1309","–1309":"–1309","1305–1370":"1305–1370","–1296":"–1296","1305":"1305","After 1309":"après 1309","1296":"1296","after 1296":"après 1296","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Écosse","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Gilbert Of Johnstone est né à Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Écosse, fils de Sir John Johnstone. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé après 1309."},"de":{"–After 1309":"–nach 1309","–1309":"–1309","1305–1370":"1305–1370","–1296":"–1296","1305":"1305","After 1309":"nach 1309","1296":"1296","after 1296":"nach 1296","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","li